         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">28/4/85 ¶  ¶ Let me thank you, dear Mr Dyer, for sending me the Kew-Report for 1882, ¶  the Museum-Guide ¶  and Mess. Bower &amp; Vines practical Botany, ¶  all of value here in a variety of ways. ¶  I am...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">85.04.28a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Thiselton-Dyer</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1882-90, f. 144.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">28/4/85</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Let me thank you, dear Mr Dyer, for sending me the Kew-Report for 1882,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. Hooker (1884a).</p>
               </note> the Museum-Guide<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Oliver (1875).</p>
               </note> and Mess. Bower &amp; Vines practical Botany,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bower &amp; Vines (1885-87), vol. 1.</p>
               </note> all of value here in a variety of ways.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>See M to J. Hooker, 27 January 1885.</p>
               </note> I am obliged also for the specimen of <name key="Myoporum%20brevipes%20">Myoporum brevipes </name>for my Monography.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to J. Hooker, 31 October 1884. M was working on B86.08.05.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The complete morphology and history of the development of <name key="Phylloglossum">Phylloglossum</name> should be very interesting, considering the odd position, which that genus occupies between <name key="Lycopodiaceae">Lycopodiaceae</name> and <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <name key="Ophioglosseae">Ophioglosseae</name>. I cannnot however befriend myself with the idea of <name key="Coniferae">Coniferae</name> and <name key="Cycadeae">Cycadeae</name> being placed near <name key="Lycopodiaceae">Lycopodiaceae</name>, notwithstanding the gigantic fossil forms of the latter. <name key="Coniferae">Coniferae</name> and <name key="Cycadeae">Cycadeae</name> are so truely dicotyledoneous as they could possibly be; and when we come to the gnetaceous forms and even <name key="Welwitchia">Welwitchia</name>, which Sir Joseph so brilliantly illustrated, we see that they ought to be kept with other Dicotyledon[e]s and have only external resemblances to spore-bearing plants. <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I look on them neither as having absolutely naked ovules; and traces of a stigmatic apparatus may be found even among the <name key="Cupressinae">Cupressinae</name>, e.g. <name key="Fitzroya">Fitzroya</name>.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M is reacting to the view of the morphology and development of </seg>
                     <name key="Coniferae">Coniferae</name>, <name key="Cycadeae">Cycadeae</name> and <name key="Lycopodiaceae">Lycopodiaceae</name>, especially the reproductive systems, <seg style="">as represented by Bower and Vines, and on the systematic relationships implied by the sequence used in the text. (Bower and Vines do not include practical exercises on the cycads.) <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>See Maroske (2006) for M's views on the systematic arrangment of plants.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I can send more Phylloglosum tubers, should you not succeed in growing the lot forwarded.</p>
